    },
    {
        "type": "highlight",
        "timestamp": "2024-10-16T13:11:52.802Z",
        "text": "Sneezing is a complex reflex that serves as a protective mechanism for the body. It's triggered by the presence of irritants in the nasal cavity, which are detected by a small compound that activates the so-called \"sneeze gene\". The sneeze signal is then processed by the hippocampus in the brain.\n\nSneezing helps to flush out old cells and can aid the immune system in protecting from viruses. The speed of a sneeze is determined by reflexive muscle contractions. However, it's important to note that holding back a sneeze may damage the surface of the nose and sinuses.\n\nThe sound of a sneeze is influenced by several factors, including cultural and psychological factors, as well as societal norms. Keeping the mouth closed is considered the most effective way to sneeze quietly. So, sneezing is not just a simple reflex, but a significant part of our body's defense mechanism.",
        "highlightedTextLength": 880,
        "timestamp_second": 661.294,
        "relative_time": 12.246185185185185,
